<style>
  @keyframes vertical-slide {
    0%,
    30% {
      transform: translateY(0);
    }
    33%,
    63% {
      transform: translateY(-33.33%);
    } /* Show 2nd item */
    66%,
    96% {
      transform: translateY(-66.66%);
    } /* Show 3rd item (clone) */
    100% {
      transform: translateY(-66.66%);
    } /* End at clone, js reset usually needed but for simple css loop we trick it or accept snap.
        Actually for pure CSS loop, we usually slide 0 -> -33 -> -66 -> 0 (jump) but jump is visible.
        Better approach: 0% -> -50% (if 2 items+clone)
        Let's try a standard 2-step infinite loop with 3 items (1, 2, 1-clone)
        */
    0%,
    45% {
      transform: translateY(0);
    }
    50%,
    95% {
      transform: translateY(-40px);
    } /* Assuming h-10 is 40px */
    100% {
      transform: translateY(-80px);
    }
  }

  /*
       Refined Animation:
       Item Height = 40px (h-10)
       Total Items = 2 real + 1 clone = 3
       Keyframes:
       0-45%: Show Item 1 (Y=0)
       50-95%: Show Item 2 (Y=-40px)
       100%: Show Item 3 (Clone 1) (Y=-80px) -> Immediate Jump to 0
    */

  .animate-vertical-slide {
    animation: slide-up 6s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1) infinite;
  }

  @keyframes slide-up {
    0%,
    45% {
      transform: translateY(0);
    }
    50%,
    95% {
      transform: translateY(-40px);
    }
    100% {
      transform: translateY(-80px);
    }
  }

  /* We need a javascript reset for perfect loop or 2 identical sets?
       Actually with 3 items (1,2,1), going to 100% (-80px) shows 1-clone.
       But we need to SNAP back to 0 without animation.
       CSS-only seamless loops usually use 2 sets and translate -50%.
       Let's stick to the 1-2-1 approach but since we can't 'snap' easily in simple keyframes without a glitch or complex % math:

       Simpler approach: Just fade in/out two absolute items?
       No, slide is classier.

       Let's use the 'double list' technique:
       Moving the entire internal container from 0% to -50% (showing 2 items).
    */
</style>

<!-- Re-thinking CSS Loop for perfection -->
<!--
Structure:
[ Item A ]
[ Item B ]
[ Item A ] (Clone)

Animation:
0 - 45%: translateY(0) (View A)
50 - 95%: translateY(-100%) (View B)
(No, percent is relative to element size. using px is safer for h-10 aka 40px)
-->
<style>
  @keyframes slide-infinite {
    0%,
    45% {
      transform: translateY(0);
    }
    50%,
    95% {
      transform: translateY(-40px);
    }
    100% {
      transform: translateY(-80px);
    }
  }

  /*
    The issue with 0->45->50->95->100 is:
    At 100% we are at -80px (Item A Clone).
    The animation loops to 0% (Item A).
    So it slides 0 -> -40 -> -80 (which looks like A -> B -> A).
    Then it JUMPS from -80 (A) to 0 (A). Since they are identical, the jump is invisible!
    This works perfectly.
    */
</style>
